Problem 1¶

In this problem we are looking at the data from a gamma-ray satellite orbiting in low Earth orbit. It takes a reading of the number of particles detected every 100 milliseconds, and is in an approximately 90 minute orbit. While it is looking for gamma-ray bursts, virtually all of the particles detected are background cosmic rays.

As with most data, there are 'features.' Your lab instructor has helpfully incorporated the meta-data into your data file.

1) Download the data from the course website (gammaray_lab4.h5), and import it into your working environment. The data has 4 columns and more than 25 million rows.¶

The columns are as follows:

  • 0: Time (in gps seconds)
  • 1: Solar phase (deg) showing the position of the sun relative to the orbit
  • 2: Earth longitude (deg) giving the position of the spacecraft relative to the ground
  • 3: Particle counts.

Looking at these graphs now, we can see there is no correlation between counts and solar phase, but there is between counts and longitude. We can also see that the counts follow a Poisson distribution of sorts. This make sense because gamma ray bursts are discrete events and appear at an average rate, so a Poisson distrubution is a fairly accurate way to describe this mathematically.

2) The background is not consistent across the dataset. Find and describe as accurately as you can how the background changes.¶

The histograms above plot showed us that the background is Poissonian (it skews to the side, but also we are measuring discrete events that show up at a "given" rate. Because the background is not consistent across the dataset, it could be that we'd need more than one Poissonian to model this data. From the 2D histogram, we can tell that the background changes around 310 degrees in the longitude. Below, I have plotted roughly one phase in the data to show the discontinuity more explicitly:

In [16]:

plt.xlabel("Longitude (deg)", fontsize = 14)
plt.ylabel("Particle Counts", fontsize = 14);
In [17]:
plt.plot(phase[:54000], counts[:54000])
plt.title("Counts vs Solar Phase", fontsize = 20)
plt.xlabel("Solar Phase (deg)", fontsize = 14)
plt.ylabel("Particle Counts", fontsize = 14);

As can be seen above, the discontinuity at 310 degrees is right where it should be. The Solar phase also has a jump, at around 250 degrees. However, this is not a new jump- we know this from the 2D histogram that we had earlier, as there was no discontinuity in the counts vs solar phase shown. As stated before, the varying background would be best modeled by multiple Poissonians (two, for example), rather than just one.

3) Create a model for the background that includes time dependence, and explicitly compare your model to the data. How good is your model of the background?¶

Because we are dealing with distributions, the results are best seen on semi-logged histograms, which is what the plots below will show.

In [18]:
mu1 = np.mean(counts[::1000000])
d1 = stats.poisson.rvs(mu=mu1, size=len(counts))
In [19]:
plt.yscale('log')
plt.hist(counts,bins=75,density=True, label = 'Data', color= 'green')

plt.title('Data vs model histogram, every millionth point, semi-logged', fontsize = 20)
plt.xlabel('Counts', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Probability Density',fontsize=14)
plt.legend(loc=0);

Looking at the plot, the singular Poisson fits fine in the beginning, but begins to change shape a lot in the tail. If we were to use this model to identify 5 sigma events (which would be in the tails), this would not bode well. Time to think of multiple Poissons! I'm dividing into two slices: the longitude goes from 0-310 and 310-360 degrees, and the solar phase goes from 0-250 and 250-360.

In [20]:
dfix1=[]
tf1=[]
dfix2=[]
tf2=[]
dfix3=[]
tf3=[]
dfix4=[]
tf4=[]

for i in range(len(phase[:54000])):
    if long[i]<310:
        dfix1.append(long[i])
        tf1.append(counts[i])
    else:
        dfix2.append(long[i])
        tf2.append(counts[i])

for i in range(len(phase[:54000])):
    if phase[i]<250:
        dfix3.append(phase[i])
        tf3.append(counts[i])
    else:
        dfix4.append(phase[i])
        tf4.append(counts[i])

mu2 = np.mean(tf1)
d2 = stats.poisson.rvs(mu=mu2,size=len(tf1))        
mu3=np.mean(tf2)
d3 = stats.poisson.rvs(mu=mu3,size=len(tf2))
mu4=np.mean(tf3)
d4 = stats.poisson.rvs(mu=mu4,size=len(tf3))
mu5=np.mean(tf4)
d5 = stats.poisson.rvs(mu=mu5,size=len(tf4))

4) Because the background varies, your discovery sensitivity threshold (how many particles you would need to see) also varies. What is the '5-sigma' threshold for a 100 millisecond GRB at different times?¶

Using the previously established slices, we can do cdf and ppf magic like always:

In [25]:
fivesig = 1 - stats.norm.cdf(5)
p1 = stats.poisson.ppf(1-fivesig, mu2)
p2 = stats.poisson.ppf(1-fivesig, mu3)
print(f"In the 0-310 range, a 5 sigma event corresponds to {p1} counts, and for 310-360, {p2} counts.")

In the 0-310 range, a 5 sigma event corresponds to 23.0 counts, and for 310-360, 29.0 counts.

3) Using your background distribution, hunt for your signal (either faint stars, or a transient). Describe what you find.¶

I am hunting for faint stars. These will be in the lower 5 sigma of my distribution (so close to zero, or possibly negative signals, assuming the data was preproccesed and the average atmospheric noise has been removed). Using my average as explored above, I can find the faint stars.

In [31]:
mean = np.mean(avgcount)
var = np.std(avgcount)
prob = stats.norm.ppf(fivesig,loc=mean,scale=var)
print("Five sigma threshold is: " + str(round(prob,2)))

Five sigma threshold is: -4.92

This means I need to have -4.92 counts in a pixel for it to be a dim star. Now let's find if we have such points:

In [32]:
count = 0
for i in range(len(avgcount)):

As you see, we don't have anything that qualifies as a discovery.

4) You and your lab partner had different pdf(), but were using the same data. Explore why this is.¶

We had different pdf()'s because we were looking for different things. I was looking for a faint signal, which would follow a Normal distribution, and appears in all the images. Aidan was looking for transient signals, which would be present in some of the images, not in all of them. This means the distribution he was looking at was different.
